## Code review fix-up: move navbar role-badge inline CSS into permissions.css

Context: Code review of the declarative-permissions refactor flagged
that ``base.html`` introduced inline ``style="..."`` on the new
``#roleNavBadgeItem`` / ``#roleNavBadge`` markup, violating
``src/.coding_rules.md`` §4 ("templates must not contain CSS styles
directly"). The initial-state ``style="display:none !important"`` also
forced ``permissions.js`` to fight back with
``style.setProperty('display', 'flex', 'important')``. Moved both into
``permissions.css`` and switched the toggle to a class flip.

Changes:

1. src/front/static/global/css/permissions.css
   New "Navbar role badge" block: ``#roleNavBadgeItem`` ships hidden,
   ``.is-visible`` flips it to ``display: flex !important``,
   ``#roleNavBadge`` carries the colour / sizing / spacing the inline
   styles used to set.
2. src/front/templates/base.html
   Removed the two ``style="..."`` attributes from
   ``#roleNavBadgeItem`` and ``#roleNavBadge`` — the markup is now
   purely structural.
3. src/front/static/global/js/permissions.js
   ``showRoleNavBadge`` now adds ``is-visible`` instead of imperatively
   writing ``style.display = 'flex'``, matching the declarative
   gating model used everywhere else in this PR.

